{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492328"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.4,0.13,0.27,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88316"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner for a health review. He has a medical history of type 1 diabetes, hypertension, obesity and stage 3 chronic kidney disease. His medications include insulin, hydrochlorothiazide 25 mg daily and perindopril 10 mg daily. He reports no adverse effects of these medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 142/86 mmHg, temperature 37.2 \u00b0C and BMI 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHome blood pressure readings show systolic blood pressure is consistently between 135 - 150 mmHg. Routine blood and urine tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 140 \u03bcmol/L (50\u2013120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.9 mmol/L (3.5\u20134.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c 7 % (\u0026lt;7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary albumin/creatinine ratio 24 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;2.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No change in management","Stop the hydrochlorothiazide and start dapagliflozin","Stop the hydrochlorothiazide and start spironolactone","Add nifedipine","Add candesartan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has adequate glycaemic control based on the information provided (HbA1c), although the patient\u0027s blood pressure is suboptimal, particularly noting the elevated home blood pressure readings which would not be affected by white coat hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. In patients at high of cardiovascular risk\u2014such as those with previous myocardial infarction or stroke, diabetes with microalbuminuria (as in this patient), moderate to severe CKD or familial hypercholesterolaemia\u2014more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u0026lt;120-130 mmHg) may be appropriate. However, such targets require careful monitoring for treatment-related adverse effects, including hypotension, syncope, electrolyte disturbances, and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, the most appropriate management approach for this patient would be to add an additional anti-hypertensive agent, with a calcium channel blocker such as \u003Cstrong\u003Enifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E being an appropriate next-line option. It is also mentioned in the stem that the patient did not experience adverse effects of his current medications (such as light-headedness) so it would be reasonable to initiate another anti-hypertensive agent with appropriate symptom monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo change in management\u003C/strong\u003E is a less optimal option given his current blood pressure and tolerance of medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no indication in the stem that cessation of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary (e.g. significant hyponatraemia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications such as \u003Cstrong\u003Espironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E (mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist) and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecandesartan\u003C/strong\u003E (angiotensin II receptor blocker, ARB) would be less advisable due to their potential to cause hyperkalaemia, given the patient\u0027s potassium result in the stem is already borderline. Aditionally adding candesartan (an ARB) whilst the patient is already taking perindopril (ACE inihibitor) is inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is a SGLT2 inhibitor used in the management of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, with other benefits including diuresis and blood-pressure lowering. There exists a significant risk of diabetic ketoacidosis with the use of SGLT2 inhibitors in patients with Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus and therefore this medication is less appropriate for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium channel blockers can be added to ACE inhibitor and thiazide diuretic therapy in the management of hypertension in patients with chronic kidney disease."],"references":["National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Gabb GM, Mangoni AA, Anderson CS, Cowley D, Dowden JS, Golledge J, et al. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults - 2016. Med J Aust. 2016;205(2):85-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27456450/","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88316"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88316"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T13:33:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T13:33:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"it